    baseText: "Defensiveness — why we do it and why it ALWAYS escalates. Defensiveness is meeting your partner's complaint with a counter-attack or playing the victim: 'It's not my fault, you're the one who...' or 'I can't do anything right, can I?' It feels justified in the moment — you're protecting yourself. But defensiveness sends a devastating message: 'Your concern doesn't matter. Your feelings are wrong.' It invalidates your partner and ensures the original issue never gets resolved. The antidote is taking responsibility — even for just 2% of the problem. Even if you feel 98% justified, find the 2% where your partner has a point and own it: 'You're right, I should have called. I can see why that was frustrating.' That 2% of responsibility does more for your relationship than 100% of your defense ever could. Today's task: Think of a recent complaint from your partner where you got defensive. Now find your 2%. It's there — it always is. Practice saying it out loud: 'You're right about [specific thing]. I [specific action] and I understand why that [specific impact].' Notice how your body feels when you take responsibility vs when you defend.",
