    baseText: "The desire paradox — why closeness can kill passion. Esther Perel's groundbreaking research reveals an uncomfortable truth: the very ingredients that make a relationship feel safe and secure (familiarity, predictability, closeness) can extinguish desire, which thrives on mystery, novelty, and a certain amount of distance. This isn't a design flaw — it's the central tension of every long-term relationship. We want security AND passion, but the conditions for each are different. Security says 'I have you.' Desire says 'I want you.' You can have both, but only if you understand that they require different things. Today's task: Reflect on the trajectory of desire in your relationship. When was it highest? What conditions were present — newness, uncertainty, autonomy, pursuit? When did it dip? What changed? Don't blame yourself or your partner. Understand the dynamic. Desire isn't lost — it's waiting for the right conditions.",
